Foundations of Data Science Project - Diabetes Analysis¶

Context¶

Diabetes is one of the most frequent diseases worldwide and the number of diabetic patients are growing over the years. The main cause of diabetes remains unknown, yet scientists believe that both genetic factors and environmental lifestyle play a major role in diabetes.

A few years ago research was done on a tribe in America which is called the Pima tribe (also known as the Pima Indians). In this tribe, it was found that the ladies are prone to diabetes very early. Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients were females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage.

Objective¶

Here, we are analyzing different aspects of Diabetes in the Pima Indians tribe by doing Exploratory Data Analysis.

Data Dictionary¶

The dataset has the following information:

  • Pregnancies: Number of times pregnant
  • Glucose: Plasma glucose concentration over 2 hours in an oral glucose tolerance test
  • BloodPressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg)
  • SkinThickness: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
  • Insulin: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml)
  • BMI: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)
  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction: A function that scores the likelihood of diabetes based on family history.
  • Age: Age in years
  • Outcome: Class variable (0: a person is not diabetic or 1: a person is diabetic)

Matplotlib is used to create visualizations in Python, with matplotlib.pyplot providing a collection of functions that make matplotlib work like MATLAB. Seaborn is another visualization library for making statistical graphics in Python. It is built on top of matplotlib and integrates closely with pandas data structures.

Q15. Create a pairplot for the variables 'Glucose', 'SkinThickness', and 'DiabetesPedigreeFunction'. Write your observations from the plot. (3 Marks)¶

  self._figure.tight_layout(*args, **kwargs)

Write your Answer here:¶

Ans 15: For the Glucose distribution, we can see that the glucose levels are distributed differently for the diabetic group compared to the non-diabetic group. For the diabetic group, the distribution peak is at a higher glucose level, which is to be expected. In the SkinThickness vs Glucose and DiabetesPedigreeFunction vs Glucose scatter plots, you can see that the color-coded groups are clusters separable by eye, showing that the diabetic group has a higher level of glucose in both plots. We can also see that the DiabetesPedigreeFunction distribution has the same shape and peak location for both groups, showing that family history does not contribute to a women becoming diabetic (the DiabetesPedigreeFunction variable is based on family history). The SkinThickness distribution also has the same shape and peak location for both groups, indicating no difference in skin thickness between the diabetic and non-diabetic groups. The distributions show higher frequencies for the non-diabetic group, which simply indicates that there are more non-diabetic women in this sample. None of the scatter plots show any notable correlation.

Write your Answer here:¶

Ans 16: There is a positive correlation between glucose and insulin, showing an increased production of insulin as glucose levels increase. These data points are most likely from the non-diabetic group. There is also a horizontal line showing that as glucose levels increase, insulin levels stay the same. These data points are most likely from the diabetic group, which explains the lack of insulin production in the presence of glucose.

Comparing the two histograms and looking at how their shapes differ, there is a much bigger drop after the 20-30 age group in the second histogram. This could indicate that it is harder to stay non-diabetic the older you get.

Q 19. What is the Interquartile Range of all the variables? Why is this used? Which plot visualizes the same? (5 Marks)¶

In [23]:

DiabetesPedigreeFunction     0.3825
Age                         17.0000
Outcome                      1.0000
dtype: float64

Write your Answer here:¶

Ans 19: The interquartile range is a measure of dispersion - it shows how spread out the data is. The higher it is, the more variable the data is and vice versa. You can use a box plot to visualize this, where the height (if the box plot is vertical, or width if the box plot is horizontal) of the box represents the interquartile range.
